Drop Redundant Columns¶

Apart from the unnecessary columns specified in proposal, 'Stn Press (kPa)' is not important because small atmospheric pressure changes have infinitesimal effects on everyday activities.

In [7]:
weather_clean = weather.drop(['Year', 'Month', 'Day', 'Time', 'Station Name', 'Climate ID', 'Longitude (x)', 'Latitude (y)', 'Stn Press (kPa)'], axis=1)
  • The 'Date/Time' column need to be converted to datetime variable and localized to 'EST' timezone.
  • The 'Weather' column is the visual observation of the weather environment and appears to be important. The missing values in this column means a clear weather. So missing values should be assigned with 'Clear'.
  • There are a number of columns containing the word 'Flag', and only contains NaN or 'M' values. According to Environment and Climate Change Canada, the 'M' represents 'missing' which means the data is unretrievable or unavailable. The flag columns can be removed since they only contain overlapping information.
In [8]:
# Look for and drop the columns containing the word 'Flag'
flag_columns = [col for col in weather.columns if 'Flag' in col]
weather_clean = weather_clean.drop(flag_columns, axis = 1)

Imputing/filling Hmdx and Wind Chill missing values¶

According to Environment and Climate Change Canada (https://climate.weather.gc.ca/glossary_e.html), the humidex values are only reported if:

(1) air temperature is greater than or equal to 20 degrees celsius and,

(2) the humidex value is at least 1 degree greater than the air temperature.

Similarily, wind chill is only calculated if the air temperature is less than or equal to 0 degrees celsius.

In [15]:
# Visualizing number of missing values in 'Hmdx' and 'Wind Chill' columns
weather_clean.resample('M').agg(lambda row: row.isnull().sum())[['Hmdx', 'Wind Chill']].plot(figsize = (10, 6))

plt.title('Number of missing values for Hmdx and Wind Chill columns', fontsize = 18)
plt.xlabel('Time', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Missing Value Count', fontsize = 15)
plt.legend(['Hmdx', 'Wind Chill'], fontsize = 14)
Out[15]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x2361272f520>

We can find that there are more missing wind chill values and fewer missing humidex values in the summer, and vice versa in the winter. This agrees with the explanation provided by Environment and Climate Change Canada.

Therefore, the missing values in 'Hmdx' and 'Wind Chill' should not be modified.

The weather feature contains weather phenomenon, and therefore the NaN values should represent a clear day. We can fill the missing values using "Clear" str.

weather_clean['Weather'].fillna('Clear', inplace = True)

Imputing/filling missing values for other columns¶

The weather data is sampled every hour, so it should be reasonable to impute missing values based on the time-adjacent valid observations. Except for 'Hmdx', 'Wind Chill', and 'Weather' columns, all other columns will have missing values filled using linear interpolation between valid observations.

In [18]:
# Linear interpolating values 
interpolating_col = weather_clean.columns.drop(['Hmdx', 'Wind Chill', 'Weather'])
weather_clean[interpolating_col] = weather_clean[interpolating_col].interpolate(
    method = 'linear', axis = 0, limit_direction = 'both').round(1)

    ]

In [22]:
# draw distplot to visualize outliers
plt.figure(figsize=(6,8))
other_columns = ['Visibility (km)', 'Precip. Amount (mm)']
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
sns.distplot(weather_clean[other_columns[0]])
plt.subplot(2,1,2)
sns.distplot(weather_clean[other_columns[1]])
plt.show()
  • Wind Dir (10s deg) should not be checked for outliers since this represent the direction of wind.
  • There is no outlier for 'Temp (°C)', which means the weather records are rather reliable.
  • The outliers for 'Dew Point Temp (°C)', 'Rel Hum (%)', 'Wind Spd (km/h)', 'Hmdx', 'Wind Chill' actually represents extreme weather condition and should not be removed or capped.
  • Visibility and Precip. Amount features distribution tells that most of the days are clear and without precipitation. And the outliers also represents extreme weather condition. So they should not be removed or capped.

Conclusion: There is no need to remove outliers. The weather data is cleaned! Note that the NaN value for Wind Chill and Hmdx should not be treated as a simple zero.

from pytz import timezone  # Import the timezone class from pytz

# Convert 'Date/Time' column to datetime type with UTC timezone
filtered_data['Date/Time'] = pd.to_datetime(filtered_data['Date/Time'], utc=True)

# Localize 'Date/Time' column to your desired timezone (e.g., 'US/Eastern')
eastern = timezone('US/Eastern')
filtered_data['Date/Time'] = filtered_data['Date/Time'].dt.tz_convert(eastern)

# Round 'Start Time' to the nearest hour and create 'merge_time' column
filtered_data['merge_time'] = filtered_data['Date/Time'].dt.floor('H', ambiguous='NaT', nonexistent='shift_forward')

filtered_data = filtered_data.drop(['DATE', 'TIME'], axis=1)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming your DataFrame is named 'data_merged'
columns_to_plot = ['Temp (°C)', 'Dew Point Temp (°C)', 'Rel Hum (%)', 'Wind Dir (10s deg)',
                    'Wind Spd (km/h)', 'Visibility (km)', 'Hmdx', 'Wind Chill', 'Precip. Amount (mm)']

# Set the background style to 'whitegrid'
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

# Create a 3x3 grid of subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=3, figsize=(15, 10))
fig.suptitle('Distribution of Accidents by Weather Condition', fontsize=22)

# Flatten the 2D array of subplots to a 1D array for easy iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Loop through each column and plot a histogram in a subplot
for i, column in enumerate(columns_to_plot):
    sns.histplot(x=column, hue='Severity', data=data_merged, multiple='stack', bins=30, kde=True, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(column)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(column)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')

# Adjust layout for better spacing
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])

plt.show()

One-way ANOVA tests¶

check the relationship between the 'Severity' and weather-related variables

In [49]:
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# Assuming data_merged is your DataFrame

# List to store P-values
p_values = []

# Selecting the target column (Severity)
target_column = 'Severity'

# Columns to check means with
columns_to_check = ['Temp (°C)', 'Dew Point Temp (°C)', 'Rel Hum (%)', 'Wind Dir (10s deg)','Hmdx',
                     'Wind Spd (km/h)', 'Visibility (km)', 'Wind Chill','Precip. Amount (mm)']

# Loop through each selected column
for column in columns_to_check:
    # Perform one-way ANOVA
    groups = [data_merged[data_merged[target_column] == level][column] for level in data_merged[target_column].unique()]
    
    _, p_value = f_oneway(*groups)
    
    # Appending the P-value to the list
    p_values.append((column, p_value))

# Creating a DataFrame from the P-values list
p_values_df = pd.DataFrame(p_values, columns=['Column', 'P-Value'])

# Displaying the DataFrame sorted by P-values
print(p_values_df.sort_values(by='P-Value'))

Chi-squared test¶

To check the relationship between the 'Severity' column and the categorical variable 'Weather', can perform a chi-squared test. The chi-squared test can be used to assess whether there is a significant association between two categorical variables.

In [52]:
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Assuming data_merged is your DataFrame

# Selecting the target column (Severity)
target_column = 'Severity'

# Selecting the categorical column (Weather Condition)
weather_condition_column = 'Weather'

# Creating a contingency table
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data_merged[weather_condition_column], data_merged[target_column])

# Performing the chi-squared test
chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

# Displaying the result
print(f"Chi-squared value: {chi2}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

Chi-squared value: 32.79432819826731
P-value: 0.24340051655223682
